# Conventions — {{.Project}}

> Go style + naming + structural rules. PRs / agent sessions that violate
> these are rejected by the reviewer.

## Naming

- Packages: short, lowercase, no underscores. `harness`, not `harness_util`.
- Exported types & functions: `CamelCase`. Unexported: `camelCase`.
- Test names describe the contract:
  `TestSetStatus_RejectsIllegalTransition`, not `TestSetStatus_3`.
- Interfaces named after the verb (`Reader`, `Walker`) when single-method.

## File structure

- One package per directory.
- Public API at the top of the file; helpers below.
- Constants at the top of their file (`const ( ... )` block).
- Tests live in `<name>_test.go` next to the code they test.

## Errors

- Return `error`, never `panic` for expected failure paths.
- Wrap with `%w`: `fmt.Errorf("read config %s: %w", path, err)`.
- `panic` is reserved for programmer errors (nil map deref, etc.) the
  compiler can't catch.

## Doc comments

- Every exported identifier has a doc comment that starts with its name:
  `// LoadConfig reads ...`.
- The comment explains *why* the function exists, not just *what* it
  does. The body shows the *what*.

## Tests

- One test per acceptance criterion in `feature_list.json`.
- Table-driven where the input space is enumerable.
- `t.TempDir()` for filesystem fixtures — never `os.TempDir()` directly.
- Use `t.Helper()` in test helpers so failures point at the caller.
- Race-detector clean: `go test -race ./...` must pass.

## Linting

- `gofmt -s` and `goimports` clean.
- `go vet ./...` clean.
- `golangci-lint run` clean if the project ships a `.golangci.yml`.
